First we show that $A \subseteq B \land S \subseteq T \implies A \times S \subseteq B \times T$.\nFirst, let $A = \O$ or $S = \O$.\nThen from [[Cartesian Product is Empty iff Factor is Empty]]: 
 :$A \times S = \O \subseteq B \times T$ 
 so the result holds.\nNext, let $A, S \ne \O$.\nThen from [[Cartesian Product is Empty iff Factor is Empty]]: 
 :$A \times S \ne \O$ 
 and we can use the following argument: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | o = 
 | r = \tuple {x, y} \in A \times S 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = x \in A, y \in S 
 | c = {{Defof|Cartesian Product}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = x \in B, y \in T 
 | c = {{Defof|Subset}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = \tuple {x, y} \in B \times T 
 | c = {{Defof|Cartesian Product}} 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nThus $A \times S \subseteq B \times T$ as we were to prove.\nNow we show that if $A, S \ne \O$, then: 
 :$A \times S \subseteq B \times T \implies A \subseteq B \land S \subseteq T$\nSo suppose that $A \times S \subseteq B \times T$.\nFirst note that if $A = \O$, then $A \times S = \O \subseteq B \times T$, whatever $S$ is, so it is not necessarily the case that $S \subseteq T$.\nSimilarly if $S = \O$; it is not necessarily the case that $A \subseteq B$.\nSo that explains the restriction $A, S \ne \O$.\nNow, as $A, S \ne \O$, $\exists x \in A, y \in S$.\nThus: 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | o = 
 | r = x \in A, y \in S 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = \tuple {x, y} \in A \times S 
 | c = {{Defof|Cartesian Product}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = \tuple {x, y} \in B \times T 
 | c = {{Defof|Subset}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = x \in B, y \in T 
 | c = {{Defof|Cartesian Product}} 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nSo when $A, S \ne \O$, we have: 
 :$A \subseteq S \land B \subseteq T \implies A \times S \subseteq B \times T$ 
 :$A \times S \subseteq B \times T \implies A \subseteq B \land S \subseteq T$ 
 from which: 
 :$A \times S \subseteq B \times T \iff A \subseteq B \land S \subseteq T$\n{{qed}}

