 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nWe have that $\mathcal R$ is not [[Definition:Null Relation|null]].\nSuppose $\mathcal R$ is not [[Definition:Asymmetric Relation|asymmetric]].\nSo, by definition, $\exists \left({x, y}\right) \in \mathcal R: \left({y, x}\right) \in \mathcal R$.\nThen from the transitivity of $\mathcal R$ that would mean $\left({x, x}\right) \in \mathcal R$.\nBut that would contradict the antireflexivity of $\mathcal R$.\nTherefore $\left({x, y}\right) \in \mathcal R \implies \left({y, x}\right) \notin \mathcal R$ and $\mathcal R$ has been shown to be asymmetric.\n{{qed}}

(In the case of $\mathcal R$ being [[Definition:Reflexive Relation|reflexive]], the property holds for ''all'' $x \in S$.)\nThus $\mathcal R$ is not [[Definition:Antitransitive Relation|antitransitive]]: 
